<hr color="#482b1d" size="1" />

<table width="500">
<tr><td>
<h2>
<img src="http://media.wwnorton.com/college/history/worlds-toegether-worlds-apart3/historytours/gearth_logo.jpg" />
Civil War Battles, 1861-1865<br/>Google Earth Tour for W. W. Norton, by Dr. Kathleen M. W. Thomas</h2>
<p>
Abraham Lincoln was elected in November 1860 with the promise to keep slavery out of the Western territories.  Although he had promised to protect the "property rights" of current slave owners during his campaign, many southerners remained unconvinced.  Before Lincoln even took office, South Carolina seceded on December 20, 1860.  While distressing, the act was not much of a surprise given that South Carolina had the highest percentage of slaves and a long history of threatening secession.  What was more worrisome was that an additional six states quickly seceded before Lincoln took office in March 1861.  The seven seceded states formed the Confederate States of America (C.S.A.) with Jefferson Davis as President.
<p>
U.S. President James Buchanan was still in office when C.S.A. states began to confiscate federal properties within their borders.  Buchanan did nothing, arguing that although secession was unconstitutional, there was also nothing in the Constitution that allowed the federal government to use force against states for any reason.  After Lincoln was sworn into office on March 4, 1861, he too did nothing to recover the seized properties.  Instead, President Lincoln stated in his inaugural address that there would be "no bloodshed or violence" and that "the property, peace, and security of no section are to be in any wise endangered."  Lincoln even reached out to the seceded states reminding them of his earlier pledge: "I have no purpose, directly or indirectly, to interfere with the institution of slavery in the States where it exists. I believe I have no lawful right to do so, and I have no inclination to do so."
<p>
While Lincoln made it clear in this speech that he had no intention to end slavery "where it exists" and that he wanted to avoid bloodshed, he also stressed that he considered the Constitution and the United States to be perpetual: "Perpetuity is implied, if not expressed, in the fundamental law of all national governments. It is safe to assert that no government proper ever had a provision in its organic law for its own termination."  He pledged to protect the perpetuity of the United States without bloodshed or violence-"unless it be forced upon the national authority."  President Lincoln was trying to coax the seceded states back into the union by reaffirming states' rights and his desire to maintain peace.  Yet everyone knew that he also had no intention of allowing slavery to expand into the western territories.
<p>
Follow this tour of Civil War battles to see when and why President Lincoln felt that he was forced, as the national authority, into using violence against the seceded states.  Also, note when and why he changed his mind about respecting the "property rights" of slave owners to own human beings.  Each side in this conflict firmly believed that they not only would win this war but would win swiftly and easily.  As you tour the battles in chronological order, think about when and why each side had to adjust their assumptions and goals.  How did their adjustments affect their military strategies and operations?  Finally, how did the changing circumstances of the war and the proclamation of individual and equal rights for all men necessitate the expansion of federal powers during and after the war?
<p>
The National Park Service's "American Battlefield Protection Program" identifies over 10,000 armed conflicts during the Civil War with 384 (3.7%) battles as having historical significance.  Of these 384 battles, we've chosen 10 that answer these questions and highlight the military, economic, and social significance of the Civil War.
