			<name>July 21, 1861, Battle of Bull Run</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<img src="http://media.wwnorton.com/college/history/worlds-toegether-worlds-apart3/historytours/norton_logo.jpg" />


<hr color="#482b1d" size="1" />

<table width="500">
<tr><td>
<h2>
<img src="http://media.wwnorton.com/college/history/worlds-toegether-worlds-apart3/historytours/gearth_logo.jpg" />
Henry Hill (12521 Lee Hwy), Manassas, Virginia<br/>Battle of Bull Run, July 21, 1861: the Making of New Generals and a Long War</h2>
<p>
After the attack on and surrender of Fort Sumter, Lincoln called upon the state militias to aid in its recapture.  Four more slave states decided to secede rather than fight against their Southern neighbors.
<p>
Read President Lincoln's inaugural address and his instructions to Major Anderson, in command at Fort Sumter, to understand why the president believed that South The Civil War, therefore, pitted eleven slaveholding states in the South against the North that had nineteen non-slave states, eight territories in the West, and four border slaveholding states.  (West Virginia would be separated from Virginia in 1863 and granted statehood as a reward for its loyalty to the Union.  It became the fifth border state.)
<p>In addition to the twenty-four states and the Western territories, the North had more than twice the population of the South (22 million versus 9 million-of which 3.5 million were enslaved), six times the number of factories, twice as many railroads, thirty-two times as many firearms, and twenty times as much iron.  Nonetheless, the North was unable to quickly win the war.  Most troops were untrained and the North had the bigger job: invade, and thereby wound or kill Confederate soldiers, while convincing secessionists to rejoin the Union.  The South, on the other hand, could lose individual battles as long as they held onto pockets of land and the loyalty of the people. 
<p>
Confederate General Robert E. Lee's initial strategy was to stay on the defensive, tire out the Union's soldiers, and make Northern civilians weary of war.  U.S. General Winfield Scott drew up the Anaconda Plan: disrupt southern trade via a naval blockade of Atlantic ports and divide the Confederacy in half by taking control of the Mississippi River.  Take a look at the critical editorial cartoon "Scott's Great Snake" to see the plan visually.  The Anaconda Plan would take time, like a snake slowly suffocating its victim, since the U.S. lacked the naval power to implement it effectively.  More time was needed to build ships, especially the new "ironclads" (see below).  Public anger over southern secession, along with the mistaken belief that most Southerners remained loyal to the U.S., led Lincoln to supplement Scott's Anaconda Plan with an overland invasion of Richmond, the Confederate capital city.  Ignoring Scott's advice that the new recruits were untrained and unprepared and discounting the overwhelming effect of Southern honor and determination, President Lincoln ordered General Irvin McDowell to attack General P.G.T. Beauregard's Confederate troops at the stream, Bull Run, near the city of Manassas.  The long term goal was to cut off the railroad and supplies to Richmond, then invade the city.  The Battle of Bull Run began on July 21, 1861, just a few months after the U.S. surrender of Fort Sumter.  Each side had about 30,000 troops (once the southern rail lines carried additional Confederate reinforcements to the battle site), but the Union recruits were too few and too green to sustain their offensive attack.  Although the Union forces retreated, Confederate troops were also unable to gain any ground.  Each side lacked the ability to communicate across several lines and units.  In addition, maps were incomplete, especially when it came to the terrain.  To illustrate the extent of the logistical problems, take a look at "The Enterprise," the private hot air balloon sent up by the Union Army to conduct surveillance.  It was only with this balloon that the U.S. realized the rebels were not on their way to invade Washington, D.C.  The balloon, however, unknowingly landed in enemy territory and had to be rescued.
<p>
General Beauregard won this battle, though many credit Thomas J. Jackson with holding ground, hence his nickname afterward: Stonewall Jackson.  Hundreds of Union troops were taken prisoner.  The historical significance was in the total killed on that one day: over 800 men died.  The U.S. sustained 460 killed and 1,124 wounded while the C.S.A. suffered 387 killed and 1,582 wounded.  Both the U.S. and the C.S.A. realized that this would not be an easy war to win.  While locals had gathered to watch the battle anticipating an easy victory for Union forces, the death toll and sight of thousands of wounded soldiers foreshadowed the coming carnage.  Take a very close look at the drawing and the photo of the Battle of Bull Run.  What would you have thought if you were one of the sightseers that day?  Could Lincoln or Lee have known this would be the outcome of an attack on the Confederacy in Virginia?  The Second Battle of Bull Run, fought in August 1862, would be much more deadly: over 18,000 casualties and another loss for the U.S.  The casualty rate throughout the Civil War would astound and humble Confederates and Unionists alike.
