			<name>March 9, 1862, Battle of Hampton Roads</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<img src="http://media.wwnorton.com/college/history/worlds-toegether-worlds-apart3/historytours/norton_logo.jpg" />


<hr color="#482b1d" size="1" />

<table width="500">
<tr><td>
<h2>
<img src="http://media.wwnorton.com/college/history/worlds-toegether-worlds-apart3/historytours/gearth_logo.jpg" />
Sewell's Point, near Norfolk, VA<br/>Battle of Hampton Roads, March 9, 1862: Ironclads and Modern Technology</h2>
<p>
After Bull Run, U.S. generals used their state militias in the West (Kentucky and Tennessee) to gain access to major rivers to supply the Union forces.  General Ulysses S. Grant was successful in capturing Forts Henry and Donelson near Nashville in western Tennessee, from February 6-16, 1862.  In response, the C.S.A. attacked Grant's forces near Shiloh, in southwestern Tennessee, catching them by surprise.  The battle raged for two days, but Grant prevailed securing another victory for the U.S.  The extent of the casualties-23,000 combined-marred the victory and vexed Unionists and Confederates alike.
<p>
Meanwhile, Stonewall Jackson secured victories for the C.S.A. from Bull Run through the Shenandoah Valley.  From March to June, 1862, he successfully diverted Union troops from further attacks on Richmond.
<p>
While these overland battles were being fought, President Lincoln was putting into place General Scott's Anaconda Plan.  As explained above, the plan consisted of the operations to capture major southern riverways, especially the Mississippi River, as well as naval blockades to stop C.S.A.'s trade with Europe.  The Confederates had been successfully courting England and were importing new weapons and artillery from aboard.  The naval blockade of Southerner ports was initially difficult because the U.S. had only 90 ships to patrol 3000 miles of seceded coastline.  The Confederacy successfully imported weapons from overseas until late in the war.  (The U.S. was able to decrease southern trade by 95% but that had more to do with inland transportation problems over the railroads.)  The blockade was historically significant not so much because it halted trade but because it introduced a new element of modern technology: ironclads.  Cladding wooden ships in iron was supposed to minimize casualties, reasoned Scott, because the North could effectively cut off Southern trade and force their surrender.  In reality, the ironclads forced the South to innovate.  It took the entire war years to build the 600 steams ships and ironclads required by the U.S.  In the meantime, the South constructed their own ironclads and experimented with technology to defend ports: primitive submarines and torpedoes.  
<p>
The first encounter of ironclads occurred on March 9, 1862.  The U.S. Navy had successfully blocked access to Richmond ports using traditional wooden ships.  The Confederate <i>Virginia</i>, the previously wooden USS <i>Merrimac</i> now clad with iron and equipped with a battering rod, arrived at Hampton Roads (outside of Norfolk, Virginia, at the meeting of the Elizabeth and James Rivers).  The Virginia used its ram to sink the Union Cumberland, then attacked and burned the Union Congress.  Over 200 U.S. sailors died on the sinking and burning ships.  Cumberland and Congress attempts to fire upon the Virginia had simply resulted in repelled fire off the iron sides.  The Confederacy was about to destroy the Union's blockade of Richmond.
<p>
During the night, however, a Union ironclad-the Monitor-arrived.  Each ship, Monitor and Virginia, fired upon the other.  Each side claimed victory.  In reality, neither had been able to penetrate the iron sides of the other. View the watercolor below of ironclads, then look at the painting of the battle (note the traditional wooden ship in the background) and a photo of the Monitor'screw.  Judging from the photos and the location of the ships, what impact do you think ironclads had in the Civil War?
<p>
<i>Virginia</i>'s captain chose to blow her up when it became clear that she would be captured by the U.S. in early May 1862.  The Monitor sank while on blockade in December 1862.  Additional Union ships were retrofitted with iron and ramming rods; several brand new ironclads were built in the ensuing years.  Overall, the Union blockade held and ironclads were also significant in capturing and holding the Mississippi River in the West.  Ironclads also promoted the development of torpedoes and submarines.  In addition, more accurate arms from Europe promoted trench warfare (see below).  These items are more commonly associated with the devastation of WWI, but think about how the advances in military technology during the Civil War, as crude and as primitive as they were at the time, contributed to the extensive casualties - and ultimately to changing the goals of the North.  Listed here are photos of the ironclads, a cavalry charge, heavy artillery, and trench warfare.
