			<name>September 17, 1862, Antietam Creek</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<img src="http://media.wwnorton.com/college/history/worlds-toegether-worlds-apart3/historytours/norton_logo.jpg" />


<hr color="#482b1d" size="1" />

<table width="500">
<tr><td>
<h2>
<img src="http://media.wwnorton.com/college/history/worlds-toegether-worlds-apart3/historytours/gearth_logo.jpg" />
Antietam Creek, near Sharpsburg, Maryland<br/>Battle at Antietam, September 17, 1862: A Picture is Worth a Thousand Words</h2>
<p>
President Lincoln continued to push for an overland campaign to capture the Confederate capital at Richmond, Virginia.  U.S. General George B. McClellan moved from Fort Monroe, Virginia, in March at the same time and on the same peninsula next to Hampton Roads, the site of the battle between the ironclads.  He pursued Confederate troops and engaged in several battles, notably the Battle at Williamsburg and the Battle of Seven Pines with a combined total of approximately 15,000 casualties.  C.S.A. General Lee, following his success at Bull Run, had been given command of the eastern Confederate Army.  Lee launched his offensive attacks that became known as the Seven Days Battle, from June 25 to July 1, 1862.  The Confederate Army under Lee suffered 20,000 casualties out of 90,000 troops to the Union's 100,000 troops and 16,000 casualties under McClellan.  Yet, Lee carried the day repelling Union forces and forcing them back to Washington, D.C.  Once again, the North was struck by the reality that the South could not be easily conquered.  Confederates, while emboldened by their victories, were nonetheless distressed by the ever increasing number of casualties.  It appeared that southern honor might just overcome northern advantages in industry, population, and territory, but at what cost?
<p>
Encouraged by his victories, Lee engaged union forces in August 1862 for the Second Battle of Bull Run.  Again, the Confederates won.  The C.S.A. hoped that their continued battlefield successes would lead the border states to secede and the U.S. to surrender.  Lee's tactics would not hold out, however, and the Battle at Antietam in September would be the most deadly so far for both Union and Confederate forces.  
<p>
The White residents around Antietam Creek in Maryland, one of the border states, were loyal to the U.S. though they owned slaves.  This was the first battle on northern soil so a victory or loss here would be extremely significant for President Lincoln and the U.S.  Union troops outnumbered Confederate troops 2:1 and U.S. General McClellan was successful in stopping Lee's invasion of the North.  The cost was extremely high:  4000 dead and 18,000 wounded in a single day for total casualties of over 22,000.  More soldiers died on September 17, 1862, than on the D-Day invasion of World War II.
<p>
Besides being the first battle of the Civil War fought in the North, Antietam is historically significant for several other reasons.  President Lincoln and many others felt that General McClellan was wrong to hold troops in reserve rather than pursuing Lee's troops as they retreated.   In addition, the relatively new technology "photography" meant that the Confederate defeat was captured for all to see.  View President Lincoln at Antietam and the battlefields as you imagine the President's and the public's reaction to these photos.
<p>
Lincoln had long been frustrated with McClellan's cautious battlefield tactics.  The President replaced him with General Burnside.  Burnside decided to move as  quickly as possible against Lee.  Burnside attacked Lee at Fredricksburg, Virginia, in December, 1862, even through Lee had the advantage of the high ground.  The result?  
<p>
Another massacre, but this time of U.S. soldiers.  Twice as many U.S. troops were killed and wounded at Fredricksburg compared to the Confederate army: over 12,000 Union casualties to slightly more than 5,000 Confederate.  Despite the Union victory at Antietam, the number of casualties and the disastrous loss at Fredericksburg meant that President Lincoln had to rethink and possibly expand the goal of this war.
