			<name>June 1-2, 1863, Raid at Combahee Ferry</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<img src="http://media.wwnorton.com/college/history/worlds-toegether-worlds-apart3/historytours/norton_logo.jpg" />


<hr color="#482b1d" size="1" />

<table width="500">
<tr><td>
<h2>
<img src="http://media.wwnorton.com/college/history/worlds-toegether-worlds-apart3/historytours/gearth_logo.jpg" />
Highway 17 and the Combahee River, South Carolina<br/>Raid at Combahee Ferry, June 1-2, 1863: Harriet Tubman, Spy, and Other African-American Military Services</h2>
<p>
The death toll and limited Union success despite tens of thousands of casualties forced Lincoln to include the end of slavery as an additional goal of the war, and thereby gain additional troops.  He issued the Preliminary Emancipation Proclamation (see above) to no effect.  The Emancipation Proclamation went into effect on January 1, 1863.  The Proclamation's significance was not in the number of slaves it freed-it freed only slaves in seceded states (where the Confederate government did not recognize Lincoln as President) but freed none of the slaves in states that remained in or were already under Union control-the very places where Lincoln had authority!  
<p>
The historical significance of the Emancipation Proclamation, therefore, was not in freeing slaves but in ending slavery.  The distinction is important.  The Proclamation consisted of several declarations: the freeing of slaves in the Confederate states but also the fact that free African-Americans could join the armed services as soldiers.  Many African-Americans had wanted to join the war effort but Lincoln had refused to allow them into the military because military service in the U.S. had conferred the rights of citizenship.  Free African-Americans had been allowed to labor for the military but had not been allowed to fight as soldiers.  Now that they could volunteer as soldiers, they were defending the country against the traitorous acts of the South.  President Lincoln was forced to make the end of slavery a war goal along with reunification.
<p>
Thousands of slaves continued to escape to Union lines in the South where the men now had the option to serve as soldiers.  In the North, African-American men volunteered and became soldiers.  They continued to volunteer despite being harassed by their white compatriots, forbidden from leading their regiments, tortured and killed when taken prisoner, and given suicide missions (most notably the Massachusetts' 54th at Fort Wagner, in South Carolina).  African-American women, children, and elderly men set up makeshift schools, churches, and homes where they worked to support the war effort.  One woman, however, stands out for her military service.
<p>
Harriet Tubman, more widely known for her efforts in establishing the Underground Railroad to help slaves escape from the South, was also a spy and soldier for the Union Army.  She was never paid and only received a widow's pension because her husband had also served, yet she is credited with gathering vital intelligence and directly participating in battles.  For example, in June 1863, after the Emancipation Proclamation had been issued, Tubman scouted and gathered information about the Confederate positions and primitive torpedo sites along the Combahee River in South Carolina.  She, Colonel James Montgomery, and hundreds of Union troops raided rice plantations along the river, freeing the slaves, and destroying infrastructure otherwise useful to the C.S.A.  Read about Congress' efforts to recognize her military service.
___________________________________________________________________________________
<p>The Emancipation Proclamation
<p>January 1, 1863<br/>
A Transcription<br/>
By the President of the United States of America:<br/>
A Proclamation.
<p>Whereas, on the twenty-second day of September, in the year of our Lord one thousand eight hundred and sixty-two, a proclamation was issued by the President of the United States, containing, among other things, the following, to wit:
<p>"That on the first day of January, in the year of our Lord one thousand eight hundred and sixty-three, all persons held as slaves within any State or designated part of a State, the people whereof shall then be in rebellion against the United States, shall be then, thenceforward, and forever free; and the Executive Government of the United States, including the military and naval authority thereof, will recognize and maintain the freedom of such persons, and will do no act or acts to repress such persons, or any of them, in any efforts they may make for their actual freedom.
<p>"That the Executive will, on the first day of January aforesaid, by proclamation, designate the States and parts of States, if any, in which the people thereof, respectively, shall then be in rebellion against the United States; and the fact that any State, or the people thereof, shall on that day be, in good faith, represented in the Congress of the United States by members chosen thereto at elections wherein a majority of the qualified voters of such State shall have participated, shall, in the absence of strong countervailing testimony, be deemed conclusive evidence that such State, and the people thereof, are not then in rebellion against the United States."
<p>Now, therefore I, Abraham Lincoln, President of the United States, by virtue of the power in me vested as Commander-in-Chief, of the Army and Navy of the United States in time of actual armed rebellion against the authority and government of the United States, and as a fit and necessary war measure for suppressing said rebellion, do, on this first day of January, in the year of our Lord one thousand eight hundred and sixty-three, and in accordance with my purpose so to do publicly proclaimed for the full period of one hundred days, from the day first above mentioned, order and designate as the States and parts of States wherein the people thereof respectively, are this day in rebellion against the United States, the following, to wit:
<p>Arkansas, Texas, Louisiana, (except the Parishes of St. Bernard, Plaquemines, Jefferson, St. John, St. Charles, St. James Ascension, Assumption, Terrebonne, Lafourche, St. Mary, St. Martin, and Orleans, including the City of New Orleans) Mississippi, Alabama, Florida, Georgia, South Carolina, North Carolina, and Virginia, (except the forty-eight counties designated as West Virginia, and also the counties of Berkley, Accomac, Northampton, Elizabeth City, York, Princess Ann, and Norfolk, including the cities of Norfolk and Portsmouth[)], and which excepted parts, are for the present, left precisely as if this proclamation were not issued.
<p>And by virtue of the power, and for the purpose aforesaid, I do order and declare that all persons held as slaves within said designated States, and parts of States, are, and henceforward shall be free; and that the Executive government of the United States, including the military and naval authorities thereof, will recognize and maintain the freedom of said persons.
<p>And I hereby enjoin upon the people so declared to be free to abstain from all violence, unless in necessary self-defence; and I recommend to them that, in all cases when allowed, they labor faithfully for reasonable wages.
<p>And I further declare and make known, that such persons of suitable condition, will be received into the armed service of the United States to garrison forts, positions, stations, and other places, and to man vessels of all sorts in said service.
<p>And upon this act, sincerely believed to be an act of justice, warranted by the Constitution, upon military necessity, I invoke the considerate judgment of mankind, and the gracious favor of Almighty God.
<p>In witness whereof, I have hereunto set my hand and caused the seal of the United States to be affixed.
<p>Done at the City of Washington, this first day of January, in the year of our Lord one thousand eight hundred and sixty three, and of the Independence of the United States of America the eighty-seventh.
<p>By the President: ABRAHAM LINCOLN 
WILLIAM H. SEWARD, Secretary of State.
