			<name>July 1-3, 1863, Battle of Gettysburg</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<img src="http://media.wwnorton.com/college/history/worlds-toegether-worlds-apart3/historytours/norton_logo.jpg" />


<hr color="#482b1d" size="1" />

<table width="500">
<tr><td>
<h2>
<img src="http://media.wwnorton.com/college/history/worlds-toegether-worlds-apart3/historytours/gearth_logo.jpg" />
1195 Baltimore Pike, Gettysburg, Pennsylvania<br/>Battle of Gettysburg, July 1-3, 1863: Union Victories, Burying the Dead, and Government of the People</h2>
<p>
With additional African-American troops (10-12% of the U.S. Army, 16% of the Navy), and with Lee making advances into the North, President Lincoln pressured his generals for more aggressive action against the rebel troops.  Lincoln replaced Ambrose Burnside with General Joseph Hooker, then Hooker with General George Meade after Hooker failed to stop Lee's northern advance.  Meade was charged with halting Lee's in the East while Grant pursued control of the Mississippi River in the West (at Vicksburg, Mississippi).  In addition, Lincoln issued the North's first federal draft in March 1863.  More men than ever were needed to pursue and stop Lee while consolidating U.S. control of the Mississippi River.
<p>
Buoyed by battle successes, Lee's troops marched and fought their way through Virginia, across the Potomac River, and into Maryland where they took supplies and free African-Americans as slaves.  Lee and other units continued north and waged their main battle at Gettysburg, Pennsylvania.  Parts of Lee's army were split and unable to communicate and coordinate their attacks, while the Union defensives held over the course of several days under Meade.  On July 3rd, 1863, Lee retreated into Virginia-again without any aggressive pursuit by Union troops.  While he lost the battle at Gettysburg, Lee assumed that with equal casualties on the Union side (approximately 23,000 each), it was simply a setback.  Instead, it was actually the last of Lee's offensive moves.
<p>
Now that Lee had been stopped, though with the heaviest casualties on both sides for the entire war, attention turned to Vicksburg.  U.S. General Grant had been engaging Confederate forces since December 1862.  There were many failures along the way, but on May 14, 1863, Grant took control of Jackson, Mississippi's capital city.  Grant and his U.S. troops proceeded on to Vicksburg on the banks of the Mississippi River.  Vicksburg was the last Confederate controlled area of the river.  Union forces engaged Confederate troops and cut off supplies to the city.  The troops and civilians held out for six weeks, but on July 4, one day after Lee's retreat from Gettysburg, C.S.A. General Pemberton surrendered.  Due to Grant's leadership, the U.S. now had complete control of the Mississippi River and had divided the Confederacy in half.  (See "Scott's Great Snake" above.)  President Lincoln promoted Grant to Commander and the leadership of the U.S. Army was finally settled.
<p>
The North reacted to the news of these two victories with muted jubilation.  Death tolls were higher than ever and Lee's army had once again escaped.  The number of casualties led Lincoln to increase the federal draft which, along with the Emancipation Proclamation, resulted in riots in New York by July 1863 (see below).
<p>
Northern turmoil and lagging support for the war, propelled Lincoln to address the public in the hopes of shoring up their patriotism and their support to end slavery.  Up until this time, dead soldiers in the U.S. and Europe had always been buried in mass graves - what were called "field graves."  The number of bodies combined with the number of dead horses from the cavalry compelled immediate solutions, especially after summer battles such as Gettysburg.  The smell alone was horrific.  The citizens of Gettysburg lobbied for a national cemetery to honor the dead at this decisive Union victory.  Four months later, on November 19, 1863, the dead soldiers had been reinterred in individual graves in the new national cemetery.  The President and others were invited to commemorate the successful battle and to honor the soldiers who had given their lives.  President Lincoln was facing re-election and feared a Democrat victory.  The President used this opportunity at Gettysburg to honor the dead and the country by recalling the sacrifices made during the American Revolution and the sacrifices still ahead if the North was save the American ideal of equal representation and government by consent.  His Gettysburg Address was short and at the time, deemed inconsequential outside of his own party.  Today, however, his words have become iconic and the brevity of this two-minute speech deemed genius for what it conveys: "that government of the people, by the people, for the people, shall not perish from the earth."  Limited rights due to race or forced labor did not enter into this equation.
