			<name>July 13-16, 1863, New York City Draft Riots</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<img src="http://media.wwnorton.com/college/history/worlds-toegether-worlds-apart3/historytours/norton_logo.jpg" />


<hr color="#482b1d" size="1" />

<table width="500">
<tr><td>
<h2>
<img src="http://media.wwnorton.com/college/history/worlds-toegether-worlds-apart3/historytours/gearth_logo.jpg" />
Fifth Avenue (between 43rd and 44th Streets), New York<br/>New York City Draft Riots, July 13-16, 1863</h2>
<p>
The first federal draft in the North was instituted March 1863: all white men between the ages of 20 and 45 years old were eligible - unless they could hire a substitute or pay the government $300.  Think of the effect this policy would have on the majority of White Northerners who could not pay for a substitute.  In addition to the frustration over substitutes, there was also tension over the Emancipation Proclamation since it changed the goals of the war to include the end of slavery.  Many white men in the North did not want slavery to expand westward, but they also did not want slaves freed to compete for the scarce number of jobs.  Finally, while the victories at Gettysburg and Vicksburg were encouraging, the mounting deaths were taking their toll among Union recruits and their families.  Lincoln increased the number of drafted men and rioting ensued. 
<p>
The draft riot erupted in New York City in early July 1863.  A strong-hold of anti-war Democrats, these politicians had been encouraging Irish immigrant men to vote illegally.  Casting a vote, however, meant that the immigrants were on the rolls as citizens and thus eligible for the draft.  The Irish were treated as bad as or worse than free African-Americans.  Immigration was an issue even in the 1800's.  Rioting Irishmen targeted African-Americans, beating and torturing them.  They also burned an orphanage for African-American children.  Along with the Irish immigrants were also poorer men who rioted against the exemptions that allowed wealthy men to buy substitutes or pay a fee to opt out.  Along with attacking African-Americans, they also attacked Republicans, draft offices, and Republican newspaper offices.  Both the New York state militia and federal troops were ordered in to end the violence. One thousand people died or were seriously injured during the four days of rioting.  View the drawings below along with the letter from William Goodell, an abolitionist.  Goodell drafted the letter in the midst of the riots.  Who and what did he and others fear was behind the rioting?
