<p>1863 William Goodell NY draft riot description
<p>
From William Goodell to Abraham Lincoln, July 14, 1863
PO. Box 4381
No 104 Wm St. New York. July 14. 1863
<p>
Sir-- Please indulge me, once more.-- It may, very probably, be my last.-- The rebellion, long smothered in New York,, has at length, broken out, openly. The riot is not, -- as the Herald of this morning dignifies it, a "popular opposition to the enforcement of the Conscription, and "an attack on the people by the Provost guard." -- nor, as the World pretends, the dissatisfaction of the militia with that particular measure, nor with any feature of your administration, other than your its war against the rebellion.-- Nor is it the work, merely, or mainly, of the low, vicious, ignorant, degraded portions of Community, who are made its unfortunate instruments.-- It is the preconcerted work of men of talent, means, and influence, determined on putting this city, with its Custom House, Navy Yard, Banks, and Specie, in possession of Jeff. Davis, without further delay. The repulse of Gen Lee has deprived them of his expected presence and assistance, and has driven them, in the same spirit of desperation that instigated the his invasion, to strike the blow, now.-- Another circumstance determined, still more definitely, the time of the outbreak. The Colored men of this City, Vicinity, & of the Hudson river region had arranged for an immense gathering at Poughkeepsie, to offer their military services to the government. The Convention was to commence to-morrow. To assault, simultaneously, as they have done, the officers making the draft, and the colored people, would be to prevent either whites or blacks from joining the Army.
<p>
Some half dozen City journals, either covertly or openly, are devoted to this conspiracy.
<p>
Mr President -- My deep and settled conviction is that if the Government to save the Country from the Control of Jeff. Davis, it must in the very first place, save its commercial and financial metropolis, New York, and this can only be done only by taking immediate possession of it, and controlling it with a strong hand. If this is to be done, at all, there is not another moment to be lost. The least dependence on our state Governor, in this emergency, I am deliberately and fully convinced, would be a fatal error, equally so as would be such dependence upon Alexander H Stephens himself. In this judgment I know I am not singular, among loyal men and well qualified to judge.
<p>
The possession of New York City, even more than the possession of Washington City, determines the issue of the Controversy-- The Government if driven from Washington might strengthen itself, by crossing to New York. But if the Confederates, or what is the same thing, the rebels of New York, the Federal Government could not long hold Washington.
<p>
Please consider, Mr. President, that, notwithstanding the staunch loyalty of a majority of the leading peaceful Citizens of New York, the city contains, nevertheless, more men, more talents, more capital, more presses, more pecuniary investment, devoted to the rebellion, than any other two cities of American, Northern or Southern.
<p>
I only add that the question whether the National Government is Supreme, has now come to its crisis, and must be determined
<p>
If the National Government is to live, it must live by asserting and maintaining its Supreme in New York as well as in South Carolina-- If it cannot do this, now, its days are numbered.
<p>
If the old doctrine of "State Rights" is to be longer conceded the National Government must go under.
<p>
Martial law, in New York, under authority of the Federal Government, and administered by a discreet head and strong hand, is, in my judgment, the sine qua non of our National existence.
<p>
Gov. Seymour has just made a Speech to the Rioters, the substance of which is -- Desist from destroying private property, and I will help you break down the Conscription - in other words, the Army of the National Government.
May the Lord give you wisdom and energy, equal to the Crisis
<p>
Very respectfully, &x
William Goodell
