			<name>July 17, 1863, Battle of Honey Springs</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<img src="http://media.wwnorton.com/college/history/worlds-toegether-worlds-apart3/historytours/norton_logo.jpg" />


<hr color="#482b1d" size="1" />

<table width="500">
<tr><td>
<h2>
<img src="http://media.wwnorton.com/college/history/worlds-toegether-worlds-apart3/historytours/gearth_logo.jpg" />
Honey Springs (present day Rentiesville), Oklahoma<br/>Battle of Honey Springs, July 17, 1863: Americans Indians in the Civil War</h2>
<p>
Both the U.S. and the C.S.A. sought support from American Indians during the Civil War, especially in Indian Territory (the area that later became the state of Oklahoma).  The U.S. wanted Indian support to help gain control of the Mississippi River while the Confederacy wanted them as soldiers and for their food supplies.
<p>
Most American Indian nations made formal agreement with and fought for the Confederates.  Read about the white's desire for "free soil for free men" and the subsequent Homestead Act ("public" land in the West taken by treaties from American Indians).  Then read these letters from Governor Rector of Arkansas to Cherokee Chief Ross.  Think about why Ross first pledged his support to the U.S. but ultimately fought with the C.S.A. instead.  The Confederacy, however, was unable to uphold its agreement to maintain federal treaty payments to the Indian nations.  The Confederacy also deserted most of Oklahoma territory in 1862.  Some American Indians then left their nations and as individuals fought with the U.S.
<p>
At the Battle of Honey Springs on July 17, 1863, the U.S. "Army of the Frontier," comprised of American Indians who had fled from the Confederates, African-Americans, and whites under the command General James Blunt, fought one last battle against Confederate General Douglass Cooper and his troops largely comprised of Creeks, Cherokees, Chickasaws, and Choctaws.  Cooper and his Confederate American Indian troops lost; the U.S. had successfully wrested Indian Territory from the Confederates.  However, because these Indian Nations had formally pledged their support to the C.S.A. - and despite the American Indians who fought as individuals with the U.S. - the U.S. confiscated half their lands in Oklahoma and ended their treaty payments prematurely as punishment.
