			<name>June 1864-April 1865 Campaign at Petersburg and Richmond</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<img src="http://media.wwnorton.com/college/history/worlds-toegether-worlds-apart3/historytours/norton_logo.jpg" />


<hr color="#482b1d" size="1" />

<table width="500">
<tr><td>
<h2>
<img src="http://media.wwnorton.com/college/history/worlds-toegether-worlds-apart3/historytours/gearth_logo.jpg" />
5001 Siege Road, Petersburg, Virginia<br/>Campaign at Petersburg and Richmond, June 1864-April 1865: Trench Warfare, Total War, and the Beginning of the End</h2>
<p>
After U.S. General Grant's victory with the siege of Vicksburg, and his promotion to Commander, Grant began a war of attrition against Lee hoping that the Confederates had neither the men nor the supplies to outlast the Union forces.  Grant pursued Lee relentlessly even after costly battles.  Lincoln finally had a general who refused to let Lee and his troops retreat in peace no matter what the cost.  And the cost was high-tens of thousands more casualties totaling around 40% of his troops and the moniker "butcher."  While it appears that Grant and his officers made several tactical errors in the initial battles, Union forces were able to replenish their troops and supplies whereas Lee was not.  For nine months, the battles raged on and the casualties mounted.  Indeed, the Confederate Congress passed a law in March 1865 to arm slaves in the hopes of replenishing their dwindling units.  During the battles around Petersburg and Richmond, the Union forces built a trench 30 miles long from Petersburg to Richmond.  There was not enough time for the C.S.A. to recruit and arm slaves.  Grant, however, was able to effectively deploy African-Americans.  The largest group of African-Americans fought at Petersburg.  In addition, the U.S. Congress passed the 13th Amendment abolishing slavery in January 1865.  With ratification by the states, African-American freedom would be constitutionally guaranteed-if the U.S. won the war.
<p>
While Grant and his troops dug their trenches around Petersburg, Virginia, General William Tecumseh Sherman took control of the western war regions.  Sherman embraced "total war" philosophy.  Also called "scorched earth," this strategy reasons that the military should destroy as much infrastructure and supplies as possible without regard to military or civilian status with the goal of making civilians surrender.  Sherman first burned crops and otherwise destroyed the civilian food supply (banned by the Geneva Convention since 1977) during his earlier western campaign in Mississippi.  Burning crops, storehouses, arsenals, even businesses and homes became Sherman's legacy (and the strategy he employed against Indian nations following the Civil War during the Western Wars on the Dakota plains).  On September 2, 1864, Sherman captured Atlanta, the Confederates setting fire to the arsenal as they retreated. The victory over Atlanta was instrumental for Lincoln's reelection as well as the defeat of the anti-war Democrats in November.  Sherman ordered civilians to evacuate, and in November, as he was leaving, Sherman ordered the remaining military areas and supplies burned.
<p>
From November to December, Sherman's "march to the sea" laid waste to Georgia from Atlanta to Savannah.  Beside destroying bridges, railroads, or other military items, Sherman issued Field Order Number 120 to "forage" for at least 10 days worth of provisions at all times, "destroy mills, houses, cotton-gins, etc." if met with any resistance, and "appropriate freely and without limit" any horses and wagons keeping in mind to take more from the rich than from the poor (especially if the poor weren't hostile).  Finally, while Grant was battling with Lee to abandon Petersburg in Virginia, Sherman was marching through the Carolinas, leaving South Carolina's capital city, Columbia, burnt to the ground by February 1865.  Sherman declined responsibility for this fire, though he had insisted with Grant that he be allowed to march through South Carolina, the first state that had seceded.
<p>
Lee finally retreated with his troops from Petersburg and on April 3rd, 1865, the U.S. finally captured Richmond, the Confederate capital.   Lincoln arrived the next day, on the 4th, and Lee surrendered on April 9th at the Appomattox Court House, Virginia.  The human cost for Grant to relentlessly pursue Lee and force him to surrender: 60,000 casualties for the U.S. while Lee lost 30,000 soldiers-about half of his army.  Victory assured with the Lee's surrender, Lincoln returned to Washington D.C.  President Lincoln was assassinated on April 14th.
<p>
Sherman continued his march through the Carolinas and negotiated the terms of surrender with Jefferson Davis (C.S.A. President) and General Joseph Johnston on April 26, 1865, according to what he believed were Lincoln's wishes.  Newly installed President Andrew Johnson, antisecessionist Southern Democrat, disagreed with the terms.  Thus began the struggle for control over the Reconstruction of the South between the states' rights Democrats and the Radical Republicans.  
<p>
620,000 soldiers had died during the Civil War, though more died from disease and infection than from the battles themselves.  The total dead in the Civil War is almost equal to all American war deaths from the American Revolution through the conflict in Iraq.  Thousands more civilians perished from hunger and disease, especially in the camps for escaped slaves.  
<p>
The U.S. government had become the largest employer in the country by the end of the Civil War, employing two million soldiers (to the 900,000 in Confederate Army).  The national budget stood at $1 billion in 1865.  Although the size of the federal government would decline after the war, it remained much larger than it ever had been due to the Radical Republican's reconstruction efforts and their western programs (free land for whites through the Homestead Act, and the transcontinental railroad charters).
<p>
The 13th Amendment, passed by Congress in January 1865, was ratified by three-fourths of the states on December 6, 1865 thus ending slavery in the U.S. The Radical Republicans in Congress opened the Freedman's Bureau to protect the rights of ex-slaves and passed the 14th and 15th Amendment establishing the right of all male Americans to due process and the vote.  President Andrew Johnson, however, repeatedly worked against the federal government intruding into what he felt were states' rights.  By 1877, the Republicans retreated from working for equality in the South leaving White supremacist Democrats and the KKK in charge.  It would take another 100 years for African-Americans to begin to receive equal rights during the Civil Rights Movement in the 1950's and 1960's.
