<p>Questions:
<ol>
<li>According to the Constitution, only Congress can declare war, but Congress never declared war against the seceded states.  The president, however, has the right to call up the state militias (today called the National Guard) for emergencies of sudden foreign invasions or domestic insurrections.  President Lincoln stated in his inaugural address that he would never willingly use violence against the seceded states-unless forced by them to do so.  If declaring secession and forming their own government wasn't cause enough for Lincoln to call up the state militias, what was?  That is, when and why did President Lincoln feel that he was forced to use the state militias to invade the seceded states?  When and why did the president feel that he had the right to call the first federal draft?</li>
<li>Explain the events during the first two years of the war that forced President Lincoln to change his mind about respecting the "property rights" of slave owners to own human beings?</li>
<li>Many white Americans at this time thought that African-Americans and American Indians were cowardly and would not fight when battles were intense.  In what ways did African-Americans and American Indians prove them wrong?</li>
<li>Why didn't the North win this war quickly in 1861?  Why did they win in 1865?  That is, in what way did the strategy of the North change?  When did it change and why?</li>
<li>How did the circumstances of the Civil War along with the expectation for equal rights necessitate the expansion of federal powers?</li>
</ol>]]></description>
